KINDER MORGAN TEXAS PIPELINE LLC
STATEMENT OF GENERAL TERMS AND STANDARD OPERATING CONDITIONS FOR SECTION 311 GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
Version 0.1.0
eTariff Information: Tariff Submitter: Kinder Morgan Texas Pipeline LLC FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC NGPA Gas Tariff Tariff Title: NGPA Section 311 Service Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: September 9, 2010 Tariff Record Title: Transportation Statement of Operating Conditions Option Code: A Other Information: Baseline Filing KINDER MORGAN TEXAS PIPELINE LLC
STATEMENT OF GENERAL TERMS AND STANDARD OPERATING CONDITIONS FOR SECTION 311 GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
I. DEFINITIONS
The following terms (such terms to be equally applicable to the singular and the plural forms of the terms defined) shall have the following meanings:
1. The term "Transporter," as used herein, shall mean Kinder Morgan Texas Pipeline LLC.
2. The term "Shipper," as used herein, shall mean the party for which Transporter transports gas.
3. The term "gas," as used herein, shall mean natural gas as produced in its natural state, gas synthesized or manufactured from oil, naphtha, coal or any other material that meets the quality standards contained herein.
4. The term "standard temperature," as used herein, shall mean sixty degrees Fahrenheit.
5. The term "standard pressure," as used herein, shall mean fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) pounds per square inch absolute.
6. The term "cubic foot of gas," as used herein, shall mean the amount of gas necessary to fill a cubic foot of space at standard temperature and standard pressure.
7. The term "Btu," as used herein, shall mean British Thermal Unit(s), and the term "MMBtu" shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu.
8. The term "Mcf," as used herein, shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas.
9. The term "day," as used herein, shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time.
10. The term "month," as used herein, shall mean a period beginning on the first (1st) day of a calendar month and extending until the first (1st) of the following calendar month.
11. The term "Party," as used herein, shall mean either Transporter or Shipper, and the term "Parties" shall mean both Transporter and Shipper.
12. The term "FERC," as used herein, shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor regulatory authority having or asserting jurisdiction to regulate matters that are the subject of the Agreement.
13. The term "NGPA," as used herein, shall mean the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978.
14. The term "taxes," as used herein, shall mean any tax (other than ad valorem, income or excess profit taxes), license, fee or charge now or hereafter levied, assessed or made by a governmental authority on the act, right or privilege of transporting, handling or delivering gas which is measured by the volume, value, carbon content or sales price of the gas or the gross receipts from providing transportation service.
15. The term "Agreement," as used herein, shall mean the Gas Transportation Agreement by and between Shipper and Transporter.
16. The term "Maximum Daily Quantity" or "MDQ," as used herein, shall mean the maximum quantity of gas that may be delivered by Shipper to Transporter on any day.
17. The term "year" shall mean a period of 365 consecutive days; provided, however, any such period which contains the date of February 29 shall consist of 366 consecutive days.
18. The term "heating value" shall mean the number of Btu produced by the complete combustion, at constant pressure, of the amount of gas which would occupy a volume of one (1) cubic foot at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.), if saturated with water vapor and at a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia) and under standard gravitational force (acceleration of 980.665 centimeters per second per second) with air of the same temperature and pressure as the gas when the products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the gas and air and when the water formed by combustion is condensed to the liquid state. The gross heating value so determined shall be corrected from the conditions of testing to that of the actual condition of the gas as delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder (including the conversion from saturated to dry conditions) expressed in Btu per cubic foot and reported at a pressure base of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia); provided, however, if the gas as so delivered contains seven (7) pounds or less of water vapor per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, such gas shall be assumed to have zero (0) pounds of water per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet (dry gas).
19. The term "Receipt Point(s)" shall mean the point or points at which Transporter shall receive gas for the account of Shipper.
20. The term "Delivery Point(s)" shall mean the point or points at which Transporter shall deliver gas for the account of Shipper.
21. The term "equivalent quantity," as used herein, shall mean that quantity of gas which is thermally equivalent to the quantity of gas received by Transporter for Shipper's account after taking into account any reductions for fuel or other reductions such as an allowance for lost and unaccounted for gas.
22. The term "Dekatherm"(Dt), shall mean a standard unit of measurement such that one Dekatherm is equivalent to one MMBtu.
II. Quantities and Service Provided
A. Scope and Character of Service - Shipper shall have the right on any day to deliver to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) quantities of gas up to and including Shipper's Maximum Daily Quantity. Transporter shall receive such gas and shall deliver an equivalent quantity at the Delivery Point(s) for Shipper's Account. Transporter's obligation to deliver gas at the Delivery Point(s) exists only so long and only in such quantity as Shipper continues to deliver gas into Transporter's facilities at the Receipt Point(s). Similarly, Transporter's obligation to accept receipt of Shipper's gas at the Receipt Point exists only so long and only in such quantity as Shipper continues to take delivery of gas made available at the Delivery Point(s).
Shipper recognizes that the services hereunder are to be performed by Transporter on an interruptible basis and may be interrupted without notice in whole or in part from time to time in Transporter's sole discretion. The Parties agree that in no event shall an interruption of service constitute a breach of the Agreement and that Transporter shall not be liable to Shipper in damages or otherwise due to any interruption of service.
B. Maximum Daily Quantity - Transporter agrees, subject to all of the terms herein, to accept on each day at each Receipt Point designated in Exhibit A of the Agreement a quantity of natural gas up to the quantity shown in said Exhibit A for each Receipt Point, which quantity shall be referred to as the "Maximum Daily Quantity." Transporter shall not be required to accept more than one-twentieth (1/20th) of the Maximum Daily Quantity during any one hour.
C. Excess Receipt Quantities - In the event Shipper has quantities of gas available from time to time for delivery to Transporter in excess of the Maximum Daily Quantity, Shipper may tender such excess gas for delivery to Transporter, and Transporter may, in its sole discretion in each such instance, accept or refuse receipt of all or any part of such excess gas. Any excess gas so accepted by Transporter will be subject to all of the terms and provisions hereof.
D. Delivery Quantities - Commencing on the date of initial delivery of gas by Shipper to Transporter under the terms of the Agreement, Transporter agrees to deliver an equivalent quantity to Shipper at the Delivery Point, but in no event shall Transporter be obligated to deliver quantities in excess of those designated for each Delivery Point as shown in Exhibit B of the Agreement.
E. Balancing -
(1) It is recognized by the Parties that, because of dispatching and other operational variations, it may be physically impossible or operationally impractical for Transporter to deliver to Shipper precisely the equivalent quantity on any given day. Therefore, any "imbalance," which shall mean the difference between the equivalent quantity and the actual quantity of gas delivered hereunder on any one day as calculated on an MMBtu basis, shall be noted and carried forward, and shall be eliminated as soon thereafter as practical. At the end of each month in which gas is received or delivered, or as soon thereafter as may be practical, Transporter shall provide Shipper with a cumulative imbalance statement, setting forth any imbalance and the basis thereof, expressed in MMBtu.
(2) Unless otherwise agreed to by the parties, any imbalance existing at the end of a month shall be eliminated as provided herein. Any imbalance which is less than five percent of the total quantity of gas nominated during the month by Shipper (and such nomination was accepted by Transporter) shall be repaid in kind by the owing party as soon as practical. Any imbalance which is five percent or greater than five percent of the total quantity nominated during the month by Shipper (and such nomination was accepted by Transporter) shall be eliminated by Transporter purchasing from Shipper any quantity owed by Transporter to Shipper, or by Shipper purchasing from Transporter any quantity owed by Shipper to Transporter. The price Shipper shall pay for such quantities owed by Shipper to Transporter shall be the higher of (i) 115% of the HSCP as such term is defined in the following paragraph, or (ii) 115% of the applicable Daily Ship Channel Price, as such term is defined in the following paragraph. The price Transporter shall pay for such quantities owed by Transporter to Shipper shall be the lower of (i) 85% of the HSCP, as such term is defined in the following paragraph, or (ii) 85% of the applicable Daily Ship Channel Price, as such term is defined in the following paragraph.
(3) The HSCP is the first price quoted for the month in which the imbalance occurs in the periodical Inside F.E.R.C.'s Gas Market Report in the section entitled "Delivered Spot-Gas Prices" under the heading "Houston Ship Channel/Beaumont, Texas" and under the subheading "index (large packages only)." In the event such periodical does not report the HSCP, Transporter shall select another comparable reported price and notify Shipper in writing prior to the end of the month. In the event such periodical or the reporting of the HSCP is discontinued, Transporter shall notify Shipper in writing of the new reported price or pricing mechanism to be thereafter used. The term "Daily Ship Channel Price" is the midpoint of the price survey quoted in the periodical Gas Daily in the section entitled "East-Houston-Katy" under the heading "Houston Ship Channel".
(4) The amounts owed by Shipper or Transporter under this provision shall be reflected in the statements rendered pursuant to Section VIII hereof. Shipper warrants that it will have good title to all gas sold to Transporter hereunder and Transporter warrants that it will have good title to all gas sold to Shipper hereunder.
F. Volume Adjustment - If, during any one-calendar-month period subsequent to the effective date of the Agreement, the daily average of an interruptible Shipper's deliveries of gas at any Receipt or Delivery Point during such period is less than seventy-five percent (75%) of the Maximum Daily Quantity for such Point, Transporter, on written notice to Shipper, may adjust the Maximum Daily Quantity downward to no less than seventy-five percent (75%) of the Maximum Daily Quantity for such Receipt or Delivery Point during such period. Transporter's notice shall be furnished within fifteen (15) days after the close of such period, and any adjustment under this provision shall not be effective until the first day of the first calendar month following Transporter's notice.
G. Scheduling - Transporter shall provide Shipper with a copy of Transporter's procedures for the scheduling of services under the Agreement. Transporter reserves the right to change such procedures at any time or from time to time. Shipper agrees to follow such procedures in requesting services under the Agreement.
III. Taxes and Fee Reimbursement
In addition to paying the fee provided in the Agreement, Shipper shall also reimburse Transporter for taxes and certain other fees as follows:
A. Tax Reimbursement - Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for all taxes which are levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to the services performed under the Agreement.
B. Reimbursement of Fees - Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any and all filing fees in connection with services hereunder that Transporter is required to pay by the FERC or any other governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction.
IV. Delivery Pressures
A. All gas delivered at the Receipt Point shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's system at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Receipt Point from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive gas at pressures exceeding the Maximum Allowable Operating Pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations.
B. All gas delivered at the Delivery Point shall be delivered at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Delivery Point from time to time. Shipper shall not be obligated to receive gas at pressures exceeding the Maximum Allowable Operating Pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations.
C. Neither Shipper nor Transporter shall be required to compress gas in order to effect delivery to the other under the terms of the Agreement.
V. Measurement Procedures
A. Assumed Atmospheric Pressure - The average atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and seven-tenths pounds per square inch (14.7 psi), irrespective of actual elevation or location of the Receipt or Delivery Point(s) hereunder above sea level or variations in such atmospheric pressure from time to time, unless specified otherwise.
B. Unit of Volume - The unit of volume for measurement of gas for all purposes shall be one (1) cubic foot of gas at a base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.) and at a pressure of fourteen and sixty-seventy three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia). Where measurement is by orifice meter, all fundamental constants, observations, records and procedures involved in the determination and/or verification of the quantity and other characteristics of gas delivered hereunder shall be in accordance with the standards prescribed in the 1985 edition of A.G.A. Report No. 3 (ANSI/API 2530) on "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas," with any revisions, amendments or supplements as may be mutually acceptable to Transporter and Shipper, unless otherwise specified herein. Measurement by turbine meter, unless specified otherwise, shall be in accordance with A.G.A. Report No. 7, with any revisions, amendments or supplements as may be mutually agreeable to the parties hereto. When positive displacement or turbine meters are used for the measurement of gas, the flowing temperature of the gas shall be assumed to be sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.) and no correction shall be made for any variation therefrom; provided, however, both parties shall have the option of installing or causing to be installed a recording thermometer, and if either party exercises such option and installs or causes to be installed such thermometer, correction shall be made for each degree variation in the average flowing temperature for each meter recording. Where measurement is by other than orifice, turbine or positive meter, standards commonly acceptable in the natural gas industry shall be used in the determination of all factors involved in the computation of gas volumes.
C. Basis - The measurement of gas hereunder shall be corrected for deviation from Boyle's Law at the pressures and temperatures under which gas is measured hereunder by use of the NX-19 formula or table appearing in the manual entitled "PAR Research Project NX-19, Extension of Range of Supercompressibility Tables," AGA Catalogue No. 48/PR (published by the AGA in 1963) and any subsequent amendments or revisions to such manual to which the parties may mutually agree.
D. Determination of Heating Value - At the option of either party hereto, the heating value of the gas may be determined by recording calorimeter or by the use of a chromatograph, a continuous gas sampler or by taking spot gas samples. The arithmetical average of the hourly heating value recorded by a recording instrument during periods of flow each day shall be considered as the heating value of the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper beginning on the day the results are available. In the event a continuous gas sampler is installed, then the heating value of the composite sample so taken shall be considered as the heating value of the gas so delivered beginning on the day the results are available.
If samples are taken, the samples shall be analyzed on the measuring party's calorimeter or chromatograph at another location. The result of a spot sample shall be applied to gas deliveries beginning on the day the results are available and continuing until the results are available from a new sample that has been taken. All heating value determinations made with a chromatograph shall use physical gas constants for gas compounds as outlined in the 1985 edition of A.G.A. Report No. 3 (ANSI/API 2530) on "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas" and any subsequent amendments or revisions to such Report to which the parties may mutually agree. Heating value shall be determined to the nearest whole Btu. The moisture content of the gas shall be determined as often as necessary and practical to determine the actual heating value of the gas stream.
E. Determination of Flowing Temperature - The temperature of the gas flowing through the meter or meters shall be determined by the continuous use of a recording thermometer installed so that it will properly record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meter or meters. The average of the temperature recorded each day shall be used in computing the volumes of gas beginning on the first day of the next calendar month after the recording period. Temperature shall be determined to the nearest whole degree in Fahrenheit.
F. Determination of Specific Gravity - The specific gravity of the gas flowing through the meter or meters may be determined by the use of a recording gravitometer so that it will properly record the specific gravity of such gas. The average of specific gravity recorded each day shall be used in computing the volume of gas beginning on the first day of the next calendar month after the recording period. At the election of the party operating such meter(s) hereunder, the specific gravity of the gas flowing through the meter or meters may be determined by means of a portable gravitometer or chromatograph, by taking gas samples or by the use of a continuous gas sampler in lieu of a recording gravitometer. In the event gas samples are taken or a continuous gas sampler is installed, the samples shall be analyzed on the measuring party's gravitometer or chromatograph at another location. The specific gravity of the composite sample taken from a continuous gas sampler shall be considered as the specific gravity of the gas delivered beginning on the first day of the next calendar month after the period of sampling. If the specific gravity is determined by a portable gravitometer or chromatograph or by taking spot samples, the result shall apply to gas deliveries beginning on the first day of the next calendar month after the test and for all succeeding months until a new test is taken. All specific gravity determinations made with a chromatograph shall use physical gas constants for gas compounds as outlined in the 1985 edition of A.G.A. Report No. 3 (ANSI/API 2530) on "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas" with any subsequent amendments or revisions to such Report to which the parties may mutually agree. Specific gravity shall be determined to the nearest one thousandth (0.001).
G. Equipment - The operator of the measuring facilities at the respective points of receipt and delivery hereof shall operate and maintain, at its expense, said measuring equipment at the points of receipt and delivery hereunder. Each party shall have access to the measuring equipment operated by such operator at all reasonable times, but readings, calibrations and adjustments thereof, and changing of charts shall be done by the employees or agents of the operator only.
As specified by Transporter, all measuring stations which it owns or operates at the Receipt or Delivery Point(s) hereunder shall be equipped with orifice meter runs, orifice meter gauges, recording gauges or other types of meter or meters of standard make and design commonly accepted in the natural gas industry in order to accurately measure the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder. At Transporter's election, a computer, transducers and other associated sensing devices may be installed to accurately measure the gas at the metering points which it owns or operates hereunder in accordance with AGA Report Nos. 3, 5, 6, and 7, as appropriate, in lieu of mechanical devices with charts. If a computer and associated devices are installed, the values for gross heating value and specific gravity may be entered either manually (but not more frequently than once per month) or as real time data if such data is available. Values for carbon dioxide and nitrogen used in supercompressibility correction determinations shall be entered as real time data if such data is available or shall be entered manually at intervals mutually agreed upon, but at least once every six (6) months.
H. Calibration and Tests of Meters - If used, chromatographs shall be calibrated by the measuring party against a standard gas sample at least once per month. All other measuring equipment shall be calibrated and adjusted as necessary by the measuring party but at least once each quarter if gas is flowing at a minimum daily average of any flow rate of 500 Mcf for the quarter, or as frequently as deemed necessary by the operator of such measuring equipment but not more than once each month. The other party may, at its option, be present for such calibration and adjustment. The measuring party shall give the other party notice of the time of all tests sufficiently in advance of conducting same so that both parties may conveniently have their representatives present. Following any test, any measuring equipment found to be inaccurate to any degree shall be adjusted immediately to measure accurately.
Each party shall have the right, at any time, to challenge the accuracy of any measuring equipment used hereunder and may request additional tests. If, upon testing, the challenged equipment is found to be in error, then it shall be repaired and calibrated. The cost of any such special testing, repair and calibration shall be borne by the party requiring the special test if the percentage of inaccuracy is found to be two percent (2%) or less; otherwise, the cost shall be borne by the party operating the challenged measuring equipment.
I. Access to Meters, Charts and/or Records - The other party shall have access at all reasonable times to the measuring equipment and all other instruments used by the measuring party in determining the measurement and quality of the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder, but the reading, calibrating, and adjusting thereof shall be done only by employees, agents or representatives of the measuring party. The charts and/or records shall be kept on file by the measuring party for a period of twenty-four (24) months for mutual use of Transporter and Shipper. Upon request, the measuring party shall submit to the other party records and/or charts from such equipment, subject to return by that party within fifteen (15) days after receipt thereof.
J. Correction of Metering Errors - If, upon any test, the measuring equipment in the aggregate is found to be inaccurate by more than two percent (2%), registration thereof and any payments based upon such registration shall be corrected at the rate of such inaccuracy for any period of inaccuracy which is definitely known or agreed upon; provided, however, if such period is not definitely known or agreed upon, then such registration and payment shall be corrected for a period extending back one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last day of calibration.
K. Failure of Meters - If, for any reason, the measuring equipment is out of service or out of repair so that the quantity of gas delivered through such measuring equipment cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the quantity of gas so delivered during the period such equipment is out of service or out of repair shall be estimated and agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper upon the basis of the best available data, using the first of the following methods which is feasible:
(a) By using the registration of any duplicate measuring equipment installed by the measuring party, if installed and registering correctly;
(b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation;
(c) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment of the other party, if installed and registering accurately;
(d) By estimating the quantity of deliveries by using the volumes delivered to Transporter or Shipper, as applicable, under similar conditions during preceding periods when the measuring equipment was registering accurately.
L. Check Measuring Equipment - Each party may install, maintain and operate at its own expense such check measuring equipment as desired; provided, however, that such equipment shall be installed so as not to interfere with the operation of any other measuring equipment. Each party shall have access to the check meter(s) so installed by the other party at all reasonable times, but the reading, calibration and adjusting thereof and the changing of charts shall be done only by the employees or agents of the operator thereof.
M. New Measurement Techniques - If, at any time during the term hereof, a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas measurement or to the determination of the factors used in such gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the method set forth in this Section V when, in the opinion of the parties, employing such new method or technique is advisable.
VI. Quality
A. Specifications - The gas received and delivered under the terms of the Agreement:
1. Shall be dehydrated and shall in no event have a water content in excess of seven (7) pounds of water vapor per million (1,000,000) cubic feet of gas measured at standard temperature and at a pressure base of fourteen and seven-tenths (14.7) pounds per square inch absolute, as determined by dew point or other moisture equipment in general use within the industry and mutually acceptable to the Parties.
2. Shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grain of hydrogen sulphide per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the industry and mutually acceptable to the Parties.
3. Shall not contain more than two (2) grains of total sulphur per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the industry and mutually acceptable to the Parties.
4. Shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grains of mercaptans per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the industry and mutually acceptable to the parties.
5. Shall not contain in excess of:
(a) Two percent (2%) by volume of Carbon Dioxide (CO2).
(b) Ten parts per million (10 ppm) by volume of Oxygen (O2).
(c) Three percent (3%) by volume of Nitrogen (N2).
(d) Two-tenths (0.20) gallons of isopentane and heavier hydrocarbons per Mcf.
(e) Four hundred parts per million (400 ppm) by volume of Hydrogen.
6. Shall have a temperature of not more than one hundred and twenty degrees (120°) Fahrenheit, nor less than forty degrees (40°) Fahrenheit.
7. Shall contain not less than nine hundred and seventy-five (975) Btu nor more than eleven hundred and seventy-five (1,175) Btu per cubic foot of gas.
8. Shall be commercially free from dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, or other objectionable liquid or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transmission through pipelines. 9. Shall be free of any corrosives which in Transporter's sole determination may be damaging or harmful to Transporter's facilities.
B. Failure to Meet Quality Specifications - In the event either Party determines the gas delivered to it fails to meet the quality specifications prescribed in Section VI A. above, such Party shall have the right without notice to immediately terminate the receipt of any gas so delivered failing to meet such quality specifications, but shall as soon as practical notify in writing the other Party of such action and the basis thereof.
VII. Minimum Quantity
Transporter reserves the right to refuse to provide service or to terminate existing service at any Receipt Point whenever Shipper's delivery of gas at such Receipt Point is less than 1,000 MMBtu during any day. Transporter's right to terminate shall not apply if the deficiency is due to interruption of service by Transporter.
VIII. Billing, Accounting and Reporting
A. Accounting Statements - For the purpose of accounting for the gas delivered under the terms of the Agreement, the day shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time and extend to 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time of the following day, and the month (hereinafter called "billing month") shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the calendar month and extend to 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the following calendar month.
Transporter shall render to Shipper, on or before the tenth (l0th) day of each calendar month (i) a statement setting forth, with respect to all gas received by Transporter during the preceding month at the Receipt Point, the total quantity and the heating value of said gas, (ii) a statement setting forth, with respect to all gas delivered to Shipper during the preceding month at the Delivery Point, the total quantity and the heating value of said gas, and (iii) the transportation charge therefor. Shipper agrees to make payment to Transporter within a ten (10) day period following receipt of Transporter's invoice for all services provided under this Agreement during the preceding billing month.
B. Late Payment - In the event Shipper fails to pay any amount due Transporter when the same is due, the unpaid balance shall bear interest from the due date until the date when same is paid at a variable rate ("Variable Rate") equal to the "prime rate" of interest published by Citibank, N.A. plus one percent (1%), each change in the Variable Rate to be effective without notice on the effective date of each change in the prime rate; provided, however, that the Variable Rate chargeable hereunder shall never exceed the maximum non-usurious rate of interest allowed by applicable law. In the event such failure to pay continues for a period of thirty (30) days, Transporter may, in addition to its other remedies under this Agreement and at law, suspend all service under this Agreement until such time as Shipper pays all past and current amounts due.
C. Errors and Disputes in Bills - In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the discovery of the error. In the event a dispute arises as to the amount payable in any statement rendered, Shipper shall nevertheless pay the total amount payable to Transporter under the statement rendered pending resolution of the dispute. Such payment shall not be deemed to be a waiver of the right by Shipper to recoup any overpayment, which shall be repaid by Transporter together with interest calculated under the method set forth in part B. of this Section.
D. Allocation Statements - During the periods Transporter receives gas from other parties at any Receipt Point provided under the terms of the Agreement, Shipper shall furnish or cause to be furnished to Transporter, on or before the fifth (5th) day of each calendar month or more frequently as may be required by Transporter's scheduling procedures, an allocation statement(s) setting forth the respective volumes of the total quantity of gas received by Transporter at each Receipt Point during the preceding billing month which were delivered for Shipper's account. Subject to the provisions of Paragraph E. below, Shipper shall be bound by, and Transporter shall be entitled to rely conclusively on, such allocation statement.
During the periods Transporter delivers gas to other facility operators at any Delivery Point provided under the terms of the Agreement, Transporter shall furnish or cause to be furnished to such other operator, on or before the fifth (5th) day of each calendar month or more frequently as may be required by Transporter's scheduling procedures, an allocation statement setting forth the respective volumes of the total quantity of gas delivered by Transporter at each Delivery Point during the preceding billing month which were delivered for Shipper's account. Subject to the provisions of Paragraph E. below, Transporter shall be bound by, and Shipper shall be entitled to rely conclusively on, such allocation statement.
E. Examination of Books and Records - Each Party shall have the right at reasonable hours to examine the books and records of the other Party to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, calculation or determination made pursuant to the provisions contained herein. Such right shall extend for a period of twenty-four (24) months after each billing month. During such period of time, if any such examination shall reveal, or if either Party shall discover, any error in its own or the other Party's statements, calculations or determinations, then proper adjustment and correction thereof shall be made as promptly as practicable thereafter. As to any reallocation of gas required because of the discovery of a metering or calculation error, the quantity of gas which may be reallocated is limited to the physical quantity discovered to have been in error or the amount of the calculation error.
IX. Creditworthiness of Shipper
Transporter's obligation to perform hereunder is contingent upon Shipper's reciprocal obligation to pay for the services contemplated hereunder in a timely fashion. Prior to commencement of service or at any time thereafter, Transporter may require Shipper to supply Transporter with credit information including, but not limited to, bank references, financial statements and names of persons with whom Shipper has recently transacted business in order that Transporter may make reasonable inquiry into Shipper's creditworthiness and obtain adequate assurance of Shipper's solvency and ability to perform. If at any time Transporter is not reasonably satisfied with Shipper's credit or ability to perform or if Shipper is in arrears in its payments to Transporter for service provided hereunder, Transporter may refuse to provide service, suspend performance of future service pending such assurance or payments, demand reasonable security for payment, require payment in cash or on a more frequent basis than a monthly billing cycle, or take such other action as is commercially reasonable under the circumstances to protect Transporter's interests.
X. Facilities
A. Facilities - The measurement and appurtenant facilities required at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point shall be installed, owned, operated and maintained by Transporter, unless otherwise specified in the Agreement. Unless Transporter so agrees, Transporter will not be obligated to provide service if it requires the construction or modification of facilities.
B. Inspection - Each Party shall at all reasonable times have access to the premises of the Party operating the facilities at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point, insofar as such premises are connected with any matter or thing covered hereby, for inspection, operation, installation, removal, repair and testing of equipment, but the operation of measuring equipment and changing of charts, if chart recording equipment is installed, shall be done only by the Party operating said equipment at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point.
XI. Governmental Regulations
A. General - The Agreement and all operations hereunder are subject to all present and future applicable federal and state laws and the applicable ordinances, orders, rules and regulations of any local, state or federal governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction; but nothing contained herein shall be construed as a waiver of any right to question or contest any such law, ordinance, order, rule or regulation in any forum having jurisdiction in the premises.
If at any time during the term of the Agreement any governmental authority shall take any action as to any party whereby the receipt, transportation and delivery of gas as contemplated hereunder and under the terms of the Agreement shall be proscribed or subjected to terms, conditions, regulations, restraints or rate or price controls that in the sole judgment of the party affected are unduly burdensome to that party, such party may cancel and terminate the Agreement upon immediate notice without further liability thereunder, other than the liability to discharge obligations theretofore accrued thereunder.
B. Filings - Transporter shall file all necessary reports and/or notices required by Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's Regulations, and Shipper shall provide Transporter with any necessary compliance information requested by Transporter in connection with preparing such reports.
C. Right of Termination - Transporter may cancel the Agreement on ten (10) days' written notice to Shipper if at any time any governmental or regulatory authority or official having or asserting jurisdiction takes any action including, without limitation, issuance of a "policy statement," whereby the receipt, transportation and delivery of gas as contemplated hereunder or pursuant to other agreements subject to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA shall be prohibited or subjected to terms, conditions, restraints or regulations, including rate or price controls, or ceilings or open access requirements which, in the judgment of Transporter, are unduly or overly burdensome; provided, however, that nothing contained herein shall preclude the Parties from renegotiating the Agreement if they so choose.
D. Shipper's Warranty - Execution of the Agreement by Shipper shall serve as a warranty to Transporter that all gas delivered to Transporter for transportation hereunder and under the terms of the Agreement shall be eligible for transportation in interstate commerce under applicable rules, regulations or orders of the FERC. Shipper will indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all suits, actions, damages, costs, losses, expenses (including reasonable attorney fees) and regulatory proceedings arising from breach of this warranty. XII. Capacity Allocation
A. Priorities of Interruption - If for whatever reason, Transporter is unable to transport all quantities of gas nominated by shippers under the gas transportation agreements, Transporter shall interrupt service thereunder in whole or in part on all or such portions of Transporter's system as may be necessary in Transporter's sole discretion; provided, however, that Transporter will act as a reasonably prudent pipeline, subject to operating necessities, to interrupt service (on that portion or portions of its system where such interruption is required) in accordance with the following schedule of priorities, beginning with the first service to be interrupted and continuing in order as necessary to the last service to be interrupted:
1. Interruptible transportation service rendered pursuant to the NGPA.
2. Interruptible intrastate transportation service.
3. Interruptible sales by Transporter.
4. Firm intrastate transportation service.
5. Firm sales by Transporter.
Within priority 1., interruption shall be administered so that service under the lowest priced contract is interrupted first and service under the highest priced contract is interrupted last.
A. Shipper's Right to Terminate - In the event an interruption requiring allocation of capacity pursuant to this Section XII persists for a continuous period of ten (10) days, Shipper shall have the right, on ten (10) days' written notice to Transporter, to terminate the Agreement. Such election to terminate shall be an interruptible Shipper's sole and exclusive remedy for any interruption of service hereunder.
B. Modification of or Additions to Facilities - Transporter shall not be required to modify existing facilities or add new facilities in order to increase its capacity for service under the Agreement.
XIII. Possession and Non-Odorization of Gas
A. As between Shipper and Transporter, Transporter shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas and responsible for any damages, injuries or deaths caused thereby after receipt of such gas at the Receipt Point until the same shall have been delivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point. Furthermore, as between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas and responsible for any damages, injuries or deaths caused thereby prior to delivery of such gas to Transporter at the Receipt Point and after such gas shall have been delivered for Shipper's account at the Delivery Point. Transporter shall not take title to gas in Transporter's facilities merely by receipt of such gas for Shipper's account.
B. In the event that either Party, at its own election or pursuant to laws, orders, rules or regulations of any governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction, elects or is required to odorize gas deliverable hereunder, then such Party shall give prior written notice to the other of its intention to odorize such gas and such other Party may, at any time thereafter, cancel the Agreement with regard to that Receipt Point or Delivery Point by giving written notice to the Party that has elected or is required to odorize such gas.
XIV. Warranty
By execution of the Agreement by the Parties, each Party thereto warrants to the other that at the time of delivery of gas thereunder, it will have good title or the good right to deliver such gas, and that such gas shall be free and clear of all liens and adverse claims; each Party agrees, with respect to the gas delivered by it, to indemnify the other against all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs (including, without limitation, attorneys' fees), losses and expenses arising from or out of any adverse claims of any and all persons or entities to or against said gas.
XV. Force Majeure
In the event of either Party being rendered unable wholly or in part by force majeure to carry out its obligations under the Agreement, other than to make payments due thereunder, it is agreed that on such Party giving notice and full particulars of such force majeure in writing or by telegraph to the other Party as soon as possible after the occurrence of the cause relied on, then the obligations of the Party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period, and such cause shall as far as possible be remedied with all reasonable dispatch.
The term "force majeure" as employed herein shall include acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of the public enemy, sabotage, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, high water, washouts or other natural disasters, threat of physical harm or damage resulting in the evacuation or shut down of facilities necessary for the production or delivery or receipt or use of gas, arrests and restraints of governments and people, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe or facilities in which the gas is used, the necessity for testing or for making repairs or alterations to wells, machinery, facilities or lines of pipe through which the gas is moved, or freezing of wells or lines of pipe or facilities through which the gas is moved or in which the gas is used, partial or entire failure of wells, processing, gathering or transportation facilities or gasification and gas manufacturing facilities or facilities in which the gas is used, the orders of any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction or the refusal or withdrawal of any necessary order, certificate or permit by any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction, any acts or omissions (including, without limitation, failure to take, transport or deliver gas) of a transporter of gas to or for Transporter or Shipper, and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the Party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such Party is unable to prevent or overcome; such term shall likewise include, (a) in those instances where either Party is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits, certificates or licenses to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such Party to acquire or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits or certificates or licenses, and (b) in those instances where either Party is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such Party to acquire or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits and permissions.
It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty and that the above requirement that any force majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing person when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty.
Either Party may partially or entirely interrupt its performance under the Agreement for the purpose of making necessary or desirable inspections, alterations and repairs, but only for such time as may be reasonable and unavoidable; and that Party requiring such relief shall give to the other Party reasonable notice of its intention to suspend its performance thereunder, except in cases of emergency where such notice is impracticable and shall endeavor to arrange such interruption so as to inconvenience the other Party as little as possible.
XVI. Modification
Transporter reserves the right, at any time and from time to time, to modify or revise this Statement of General Terms and Standard Operating Conditions. Such modification or revisions shall be provided in writing to Shipper.
XVII. TERM
In the event the Agreement does not provide for a term, the Agreement shall become effective on the date of execution of the Agreement and shall remain in full force and effect through the end of the calendar month and thereafter for successive periods of one (1) month unless cancelled by either Party by giving to the other Party not less than ten (10) days written notice prior to the end of a month.
Termination shall not discharge any obligations accrued under the Agreement, including the obligations to correct imbalances which shall be corrected within thirty (30) days unless otherwise agreed by the Parties.
XVIII. RATE ELECTION
Transporter has elected to utilize the provisions of Section 284.123(b)(1)(i)(A) of FERC’s Regulations to establish the maximum rates which Transporter may charge for interruptible transportation service rendered pursuant to NGPA Section 311(a)(2).
